{
  "Which kinematic equation relates velocity, initial velocity, acceleration, and time?": "",
  "s = ut + ½at²": "",
  "v = u + at": "",
  "v² = u² + 2as": "",
  "s = ½(u + v)t": "",
  "The first equation of motion v = u + at directly links final velocity (v) to initial velocity (u), acceleration (a), and time (t).": "",
  "Which kinematic equation is used to find displacement when you know initial velocity, time, and acceleration?": "",
  "a = Δv/Δt": "",
  "s = ut + ½at² gives displacement as a function of initial velocity, acceleration, and time. It is derived by integrating v = u + at with respect to time.": "",
  "Which kinematic equation relates final velocity, initial velocity, acceleration, and displacement without time?": "",
  "s = vt − ½at²": "",
  "v² = u² + 2as eliminates time and directly connects velocity and displacement. It is obtained by combining v = u + at with s = ½(u + v)t.": "",
  "An object starts from rest and accelerates at 4 m/s² for 3 seconds. What is its final velocity?": "",
  "7 m/s": "",
  "36 m/s": "",
  "12 m/s": "",
  "4 m/s": "",
  "Using v = u + at with u = 0: v = 0 + 4(3) = 12 m/s.": "",
  "An object starts from rest and accelerates at 2 m/s² for 5 seconds. What displacement does it cover?": "",
  "5 m": "",
  "10 m": "",
  "50 m": "",
  "25 m": "",
  "Using s = ut + ½at² with u = 0: s = 0 + ½(2)(25) = 25 m.": "",
  "A car traveling at 20 m/s brakes and stops in 4 seconds. What is the acceleration?": "",
  "−20 m/s²": "",
  "−5 m/s²": "",
  "5 m/s²": "",
  "−4 m/s²": "",
  "Using v = u + at: 0 = 20 + a(4) → a = −20/4 = −5 m/s². The negative sign indicates deceleration.": "",
  "What does the variable 'u' represent in the kinematic equations?": "",
  "Initial velocity": "",
  "Final velocity": "",
  "Displacement": "",
  "Acceleration": "",
  "In the standard kinematic equations (v = u + at, s = ut + ½at², v² = u² + 2as), u represents the initial velocity at time t = 0.": "",
  "The kinematic equations apply only when which condition is met?": "",
  "There is no friction": "",
  "Velocity is constant": "",
  "The object moves in a circle": "",
  "Acceleration is constant": "",
  "The standard kinematic equations (SUVAT equations) are derived assuming constant (uniform) acceleration. They do not apply when acceleration changes with time.": "",
  "An object has initial velocity 10 m/s and accelerates at 3 m/s² for 4 seconds. What is the displacement?": "",
  "52 m — using the formula s = u + at squared gives s = 10 + 3 times 16 = 10 + 48 = 52 m of total displacement traveled": "",
  "124 m — multiplying all three values together gives s = u times a times t = 10 times 3 times 4 = 120 plus 4 = 124 m displacement": "",
  "64 m — s = 10(4) + ½(3)(16) = 40 + 24 = 64 m": "",
  "40 m — using only the first term of the equation gives s = ut = 10 times 4 = 40 m, ignoring the acceleration contribution": "",
  "s = ut + ½at² = 10(4) + ½(3)(4²) = 40 + 24 = 64 m.": "",
  "How many standard kinematic equations are there for constant acceleration in one dimension?": "",
  "Two — there are only two fundamental kinematic equations, and any others are simply restatements using different variable arrangements": "",
  "Ten — there are ten independent kinematic equations because each combination of the five variables produces a unique relationship": "",
  "One — there is only one master kinematic equation from which all motion relationships can be directly read without rearrangement": "",
  "Four (sometimes listed as three main equations plus one auxiliary)": "",
  "There are typically four kinematic equations: v = u + at, s = ut + ½at², v² = u² + 2as, and s = ½(u + v)t. Any one can be derived from the other three.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the equations of motion?": "",
  "Equations that describe the forces acting on an object, including gravity, friction, and normal force, to predict the net force and resulting motion": "",
  "Any equation used in any branch of physics, including thermodynamics, electromagnetism, optics, and quantum mechanics, not just kinematics": "",
  "Formulas that only apply to objects in free fall under gravity, and cannot be used for objects that are launched, braking, or moving horizontally": "",
  "A set of mathematical relationships that connect displacement, initial velocity, final velocity, acceleration, and time for an object under constant acceleration": "",
  "The equations of motion (kinematic equations) relate five variables (s, u, v, a, t) for uniformly accelerated motion. Each equation omits one variable.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes constant (uniform) acceleration?": "",
  "Acceleration that remains the same in both magnitude and direction throughout the entire motion": "",
  "Acceleration that is always equal to gravity": "",
  "Acceleration that increases steadily over time": "",
  "Any acceleration in a straight line": "",
  "Constant acceleration means the rate of change of velocity does not vary with time — the velocity increases (or decreases) by equal amounts in equal time intervals.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes initial velocity?": "",
  "The velocity when acceleration becomes zero": "",
  "The velocity of an object at the start of the time interval being analyzed, often denoted u or v₀": "",
  "The maximum velocity reached": "",
  "The velocity at the exact midpoint of a journey": "",
  "Initial velocity (u or v₀) is the velocity at time t = 0 for the interval under consideration. It serves as a starting condition for the kinematic equations.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes final velocity?": "",
  "The velocity of an object at the end of the time interval being analyzed, denoted v": "",
  "The velocity just before the object stops permanently": "",
  "The velocity at the midpoint of the journey": "",
  "The fastest speed achieved during motion": "",
  "Final velocity (v) is the velocity at the end of the chosen time interval. In v = u + at, it represents the velocity after time t has elapsed.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes displacement in the context of kinematic equations?": "",
  "The total path length traveled by an object": "",
  "The straight-line distance and direction from the initial position to the final position of an object, denoted s": "",
  "The change in acceleration over time": "",
  "The speed multiplied by acceleration": "",
  "Displacement (s) is a vector quantity representing the change in position. In uniform acceleration, s = ut + ½at² or s = ½(u + v)t.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a SUVAT equation?": "",
  "A special equation developed specifically for circular motion, relating centripetal acceleration to the radius and angular velocity of a revolving object": "",
  "An acronym for a particular type of force equation that connects applied force, mass, friction coefficient, and the resulting net acceleration": "",
  "One of the kinematic equations named after the five variables they relate: displacement (s), initial velocity (u), final velocity (v), acceleration (a), and time (t)": "",
  "Equations used exclusively in the United Kingdom physics curriculum and not recognized or applicable in other international education systems": "",
  "SUVAT stands for the five kinematic variables. Each SUVAT equation relates four of these five variables, making it possible to solve for any unknown given three knowns.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes deceleration?": "",
  "Acceleration that always points in the downward direction, since deceleration can only occur when an object is moving vertically against gravity": "",
  "Any negative number that appears in a physics equation, regardless of whether it represents velocity, displacement, force, or some other quantity": "",
  "Acceleration that acts opposite to the direction of motion, causing the object to slow down — represented by a negative value of a when velocity is positive": "",
  "The complete absence of acceleration, meaning the object maintains a perfectly constant velocity with no change in speed or direction at all": "",
  "Deceleration is not a separate physical quantity — it is acceleration directed opposite to motion. When an object with positive velocity has negative acceleration, it slows down (decelerates).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes free fall in the context of kinematic equations?": "",
  "Motion in which the object has zero velocity at all times, remaining perfectly stationary at a fixed location throughout the entire observation period": "",
  "Falling at a speed that is always exactly equal to the gravitational constant g, never accelerating beyond or decelerating below that fixed speed value": "",
  "Motion under the sole influence of gravity with constant acceleration g ≈ 9.8 m/s² directed downward, with no air resistance": "",
  "Any motion in which an object moves in a downward direction, regardless of whether engines, air resistance, or other forces are also acting on it": "",
  "Free fall is a special case of constant acceleration where the only influence is gravity. In this case a = g ≈ 9.8 m/s² downward. The kinematic equations apply directly with a = ±g.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the time of flight?": "",
  "The time an object spends at its highest point in the trajectory, where velocity momentarily equals zero before the object begins falling back down": "",
  "The total time an object remains in motion from launch to landing, calculable from the kinematic equations by setting final displacement to zero": "",
  "The time required for an object to reach its maximum speed during the acceleration phase, after which the object coasts at constant velocity": "",
  "The time required for one complete revolution of an object moving in a circular path, also known as the orbital period of the circular motion": "",
  "Time of flight is the total duration of a projectile's or thrown object's trip. For vertical motion returning to the same height: T = 2u/g.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes uniform motion?": "",
  "Motion that is uniform in color and shape": "",
  "Any motion described by Newton's laws": "",
  "Motion at constant velocity (zero acceleration), where the kinematic equations simplify to s = vt": "",
  "Motion in a perfect circle": "",
  "Uniform motion means a = 0. The kinematic equations reduce to v = u (velocity doesn't change) and s = ut (displacement increases linearly with time).": "",
  "A sprinter starts from rest and accelerates at 3 m/s² for 4 seconds. How far does she run in that time?": "",
  "48 m — using s = at squared without the one-half factor gives s = 3 times 16 = 48 m, which represents the distance at full acceleration rate": "",
  "12 m — using s = at gives s = 3 times 4 = 12 m, since distance equals the product of acceleration and time in uniformly accelerated motion": "",
  "6 m — using s = half times a times t gives s = 0.5 times 3 times 4 = 6 m, forgetting to square the time value in the displacement formula": "",
  "24 m — s = ut + ½at² = 0 + ½(3)(16) = 24 m": "",
  "s = ut + ½at² = 0 + ½(3)(4²) = 0 + 24 = 24 m.": "",
  "A car is traveling at 25 m/s and brakes uniformly to a stop over a distance of 62.5 m. What is the deceleration?": "",
  "−25 m/s² — using a = v minus u divided by s gives a = (0 minus 25) divided by 1 = −25 m/s², confusing distance with time in the formula": "",
  "−5 m/s² — using v² = u² + 2as: 0 = 625 + 2a(62.5) → a = −625/125 = −5 m/s²": "",
  "−10 m/s² — using a = u divided by s gives a = 25 divided by 2.5 = 10 m/s² with a negative sign added, yielding −10 m/s² deceleration": "",
  "−2.5 m/s² — using a = u divided by 2s gives a = 25 divided by 125 = 0.2 then inverted to 2.5 m/s² with a negative sign for braking": "",
  "v² = u² + 2as → 0 = 625 + 125a → a = −625/125 = −5 m/s². The negative sign correctly indicates deceleration.": "",
  "A stone is thrown vertically upward at 15 m/s. Using g = 10 m/s², how long does it take to reach its highest point?": "",
  "1.5 s — at the top v = 0, so 0 = 15 − 10t → t = 1.5 s": "",
  "0.75 s — using t = u divided by 2g gives t = 15 divided by 20 = 0.75 s, which accounts for both the upward and downward phases": "",
  "3.0 s — this is the total flight time (up and back down), obtained by doubling the time to the highest point using t = 2u divided by g": "",
  "15 s — using t = u divided by 1 gives t = 15 s, mistakenly treating the initial velocity value as the time to reach the highest point": "",
  "At the highest point, v = 0. Using v = u + at: 0 = 15 + (−10)t → t = 15/10 = 1.5 s.": "",
  "A motorcycle accelerates from 10 m/s to 30 m/s over a distance of 200 m. What is the acceleration?": "",
  "2 m/s² — v² = u² + 2as: 900 = 100 + 400a → a = 800/400 = 2 m/s²": "",
  "0.1 m/s² — using a = (v minus u) divided by s gives a = 20 divided by 200 = 0.1 m/s², confusing displacement with time in the calculation": "",
  "1 m/s² — using a = (v minus u) divided by 2s gives a = 20 divided by 400 = 0.05, then rounding up to approximately 1 m/s² acceleration": "",
  "4 m/s² — using a = (v squared minus u squared) divided by s gives a = 800 divided by 200 = 4 m/s², forgetting the factor of 2 in the formula": "",
  "v² = u² + 2as: 30² = 10² + 2a(200) → 900 = 100 + 400a → a = 800/400 = 2 m/s².": "",
  "Two students solve the same problem. Student A uses v = u + at and Student B uses v² = u² + 2as. Both get the same final velocity. Is this expected?": "",
  "No — different kinematic equations always give different numerical answers because each equation models a different aspect of the physical situation": "",
  "Only if the initial velocity is exactly zero, because the kinematic equations are only consistent with each other when the object starts from rest": "",
  "Only if the acceleration is exactly zero, since the equations diverge and give conflicting results whenever there is any nonzero acceleration present": "",
  "Yes — all kinematic equations are derived from the same assumptions and are mathematically equivalent; they must give consistent answers for the same physical situation": "",
  "All SUVAT equations are derived from the same two fundamental relationships (v = u + at and s = ½(u + v)t) under constant acceleration. They are algebraically consistent and always give the same results.": "",
  "A ball rolling on a flat surface at 12 m/s decelerates at 2 m/s² due to friction. When the ball stops, a student calculates the distance as s = v² − u² / 2a = (0 − 144) / (2 × −2) = 36 m. Is this correct?": "",
  "No — the answer should be negative": "",
  "No — you cannot use this equation for deceleration": "",
  "Yes — using v² = u² + 2as rearranged: s = (v² − u²)/(2a) = (0 − 144)/(−4) = 36 m": "",
  "No — the formula should give 72 m": "",
  "s = (v² − u²)/(2a) = (0 − 144)/(2 × −2) = (−144)/(−4) = 36 m. The two negatives cancel, giving a positive displacement as expected for forward motion while braking.": "",
  "A rocket accelerates at 15 m/s² from rest for 10 seconds, then its engines cut out and it decelerates at 10 m/s² until it stops. What is the total distance traveled?": "",
  "1500 m — using only the first phase: s = half times 15 times 100 = 750 m then doubling for the deceleration phase gives a total of 1500 m distance": "",
  "2250 m — using s = v times t for both phases: 150 times 10 = 1500 m plus 150 times 15 divided by 2 = 1125, total is roughly 2250 m distance": "",
  "750 m — calculating only the acceleration phase distance: s = half times 15 times 100 = 750 m and ignoring the coasting and deceleration phases": "",
  "1875 m — Phase 1: s₁ = ½(15)(100) = 750 m, v₁ = 150 m/s. Phase 2: s₂ = (0 − 150²) / (2 × −10) = 1125 m. Total = 750 + 1125 = 1875 m": "",
  "Phase 1: v₁ = 0 + 15(10) = 150 m/s; s₁ = ½(15)(10²) = 750 m. Phase 2: s₂ = (0 − 22500)/(−20) = 1125 m. Total = 750 + 1125 = 1875 m.": "",
  "An elevator starts from rest, accelerates upward at 1.5 m/s² for 4 s, moves at constant velocity for 8 s, then decelerates at 1.5 m/s² for 4 s. What is the total distance?": "",
  "72 m — Phase 1: s = half times 1.5 times 16 = 12 m; Phase 2: s = 6 times 8 = 48 m; Phase 3: s = 12 m; Total = 12 + 48 + 12 = 72 m traveled": "",
  "36 m — using only the constant velocity phase and halving it: s = 6 times 8 divided by 2 = 24 m, plus 12 m from the other phases = 36 m total": "",
  "48 m — counting only the constant velocity middle phase: s = 6 times 8 = 48 m and treating the acceleration and deceleration as contributing zero": "",
  "60 m — Phase 1: s₁ = ½(1.5)(16) = 12 m (reaches 6 m/s); Phase 2: s₂ = 6 × 8 = 48 m; Phase 3: s₃ = 6(4) − ½(1.5)(16) = 12 m; Total = 12 + 48 + 12 = 72 m": "",
  "Phase 1: v = 1.5(4) = 6 m/s, s₁ = ½(1.5)(16) = 12 m. Phase 2: s₂ = 6(8) = 48 m. Phase 3: s₃ = 6(4) − ½(1.5)(16) = 24 − 12 = 12 m. Total = 72 m.": "",
  "A police car starts from rest and accelerates at 4 m/s². A speeding car passes it at a constant 20 m/s. How long until the police car catches the speeding car?": "",
  "20 s — dividing the speeder's velocity by the police acceleration gives t = v divided by a = 20 divided by 4 = 5, then doubling yields 20 seconds": "",
  "4 s — dividing the police acceleration by the speeder's velocity gives t = a divided by v = 4 divided by 20 = 0.2, then inverting yields about 4 s": "",
  "5 s — using the average velocity method: the police car's average speed equals half the speeder's speed at t = 5 s, so they meet at t = 5 seconds": "",
  "10 s — set distances equal: ½(4)t² = 20t → 2t² = 20t → t = 10 s (ignoring t = 0)": "",
  "Police: s₁ = ½(4)t² = 2t². Speeder: s₂ = 20t. Setting equal: 2t² = 20t → t(2t − 20) = 0 → t = 10 s (t = 0 is the starting point).": "",
  "A student writes s = ut + ½at² and substitutes u = 0, a = 9.8, t = 3 to calculate how far an object falls from rest in 3 seconds. She gets 44.1 m. Her friend says the answer is wrong because she didn't include a negative sign. Who is correct?": "",
  "The student is always correct — distance can never be negative under any circumstances, so using a positive value of g is the only valid approach in physics": "",
  "The friend is always correct — the acceleration due to gravity must always carry a negative sign regardless of coordinate system or direction conventions": "",
  "Both can be correct depending on the coordinate system — if downward is positive, s = +44.1 m is the distance fallen; if upward is positive, s = −44.1 m but the distance is still 44.1 m": "",
  "Neither student is correct — the entire calculation itself contains a mathematical error because the formula s = ut + half at squared does not apply here": "",
  "The sign of g depends on the chosen coordinate system. With downward positive, a = +9.8 m/s² and s = +44.1 m. With upward positive, a = −9.8 m/s² and s = −44.1 m. Both give 44.1 m fallen.": ""
